nodes.body: I'm not 100% sure this is the right approach. I'd advocate for going via `AddCircle`: we should prove that for any `0 < T`, the natural quotient map from `ℝ` to `AddCircle T` is a partial equiv resp. local homemorph, and then show that `AddCircle.toCircle` is a homeomorphism `AddCircle T → circle`.

I agree that this isn't really the right approach. But I think the right approach is probably to do the full "quotient by discrete subgroup" theory and deduce `PartialEquiv` and `PartialHomeomorph` from that. In the meantime, it seems fine to add these constructions manually?

If you do want the corresponding constructions for `AddCircle`, it might currently be easiest to construct them from `circle` rather than the other way around since currently `AddCircle.toCircle` imports `Analysis/SpecialFunctions/Complex/Circle` (although that could be changed).

> I agree that this isn't really the right approach. But I think the right approach is probably to do the full "quotient by discrete subgroup" theory and deduce `PartialEquiv` and `PartialHomeomorph` from that. In the meantime, it seems fine to add these constructions manually?

My point is that in the current state of the library it would still probably be easier to go via AddCircle, since there is already a lot of API present for equivalences between AddCircle and various kinds of intervals. Moreover, this would work over arbitrary linearly ordered rings, rather than being specific to the reals.

> If you do want the corresponding constructions for `AddCircle`, it might currently be easiest to construct them from `circle` rather than the other way around since currently `AddCircle.toCircle` imports `Analysis/SpecialFunctions/Complex/Circle` (although that could be changed).

Well, AddCircle.toCircle is the map between both kinds of circle, so of course the file defining it needs to import the files defining both. But most of the AddCircle API is defined elsewhere.
Good point about generalizing beyond the reals. I'll give it a shot.

LGTM, thanks!

I believe `where` & without brackets is preferred style in lean4:
```suggestion
/-- The quotient map `𝕜 → AddCircle p` as a partial homeomorphism. -/
def partialHomeomorphCoe [DiscreteTopology (zmultiples p)] : PartialHomeomorph 𝕜 (AddCircle p) where
  toFun := (↑)
  invFun := (equivIco p a ·)
  source := Ioo a (a + p)
  target := {↑a}ᶜ
  map_source' _ hx hx' := hx.1.ne' ((coe_eq_coe_iff_of_mem_Ico (Ioo_subset_Ico_self hx)
    (left_mem_Ico.mpr (lt_add_of_pos_right a hp.out))).mp (mem_singleton_iff.1 hx'))
  map_target' := fun x hx ↦ (eq_left_or_mem_Ioo_of_mem_Ico (equivIco p a x).2).resolve_left
    (hx ∘ ((equivIco p a).symm_apply_apply x).symm.trans ∘ congrArg _)
  left_inv' x hx := congrArg _ ((equivIco p a).apply_symm_apply ⟨x, Ioo_subset_Ico_self hx⟩)
  right_inv' x _ := (equivIco p a).symm_apply_apply x
  open_source := isOpen_Ioo
  open_target := isOpen_compl_singleton
  continuousOn_toFun := (AddCircle.continuous_mk' p).continuousOn
  continuousOn_invFun := ContinuousAt.continuousOn
      (fun _ ↦ continuousAt_subtype_val.comp ∘ continuousAt_equivIco p a)
```

Do you see this as being useful in its own right, or just a stepping-stone to `isLocalHomeomorph_coe`? If the former, it might be worth adding a couple of accompanying `rfl`-lemmas (so users don't have to immediately unfold the definition to prove anything about it).
I've tagged the definition with `@simps` to add these `rfl`-lemmas.

```suggestion
  obtain ⟨b, hb⟩ := exists_between (sub_lt_self a hp.out)
```

Maybe it might be useful to add some rfl-lemmas here. (I see that you have a `change` in the other file where you apply this; I think that whenever you're having to use `change`, it's generally worth asking if that's a sign that some API is missing.)
Again, this can be reformatted in a more lean4-idomatic style using `where`

This whole proof can be telescoped down to
```suggestion
      rw [continuous_iff_continuousAt]
      intro x
      apply (continuousAt_arg_coe_angle (ne_zero_of_mem_circle x)).comp
        continuousAt_subtype_val
```
(strangely `exact` does not work in place of `apply` in the last line, I don't know why)
See comments on the other file.
can you run `#minimize_imports` on this file? I think there is some redundancy here
Can `simps` generate some of these theorems?
